30 Sec. 9.5. Owners of the following property may not be included
31 within the territory of a district and the owners of such property
32 shall not be considered in determining whether the petition
33 signature requirements under section 13 of this chapter are met:
34 (1) Any property that receives a homestead standard
35 deduction under IC 6-1.1-12-37.
36 (2) Any property that is used for single family residential
37 housing.
38 (3) Any property that is used for multi-unit residential
39 housing.
40 In addition, the property described in this section shall not be
41 subject to a special assessment under this chapter.
42 Sec. 10. Subject to section 9.5 of this chapter, the territory of a
HB 1144—LS 6588/DI 129

4
1 tourism improvement district:
2 (1) in the case of a municipality, may include only territory
3 within the municipality; or
4 (2) in the case of a county, may include only territory of the
5 county that is not within any municipality in the county.
6 Sec. 11. (a) A special assessment on businesses located within the
7 district shall be levied on the basis of the estimated benefit to the
8 businesses within the district. The unit's legislative body may use
9 the classification of the types of businesses described in section
10 9(c)(5) of this chapter in determining the benefit to a business
11 provided by the district.
12 (b) The special assessment that may be levied on businesses
13 located within the district may take any form that confers benefits
14 to the assessed business and may include any combination of the
15 following methods:
16 (1) A percentage rate per transaction at a business within the
17 district.
18 (2) A fixed rate per transaction per day at a business within
19 the district.
20 (3) A percentage of gross sales at a business within the
21 district.
22 (c) The special assessment may be levied on different types of
23 businesses located within the district and is not required to be
24 levied on the same basis or at the same rate.
25 Sec. 12. (a) After receipt of a petition under section 9 of this
26 chapter, the clerk of the municipality or the county auditor shall,
27 in the manner provided by IC 5-3-1, publish notice of a hearing on
28 the proposed district. The clerk of the municipality or the county
29 auditor shall mail a copy of the notice to each owner within the
30 proposed district. The notice must include the boundaries of the
31 proposed district, a description of the proposed activities and
32 improvements, the proposed formula for determining the
33 percentage of the total benefit to be received by each business, the
34 method of determining the benefit received by each business, and
35 the hearing date. The date of the hearing may not be more than
36 sixty (60) days after the date on which the notice is mailed.
37 (b) At the public hearing under subsection (a), the legislative
38 body shall hear all owners in the proposed district (who appear
39 and request to be heard) upon the questions of:
40 (1) the sufficiency of the notice;
41 (2) whether the proposed activities and improvements are of
42 public utility and benefit;
HB 1144—LS 6588/DI 129

5
1 (3) whether the formula or method to be used for the
2 assessment of special benefits is appropriate;
3 (4) whether the district contains all, or more or less than all,
4 of the territory specially benefited by the activities and
5 improvements; and
6 (5) whether each individual business owner:
7 (A) that did not sign to approve the petition; and
8 (B) would be subject to the assessment of the district that
9 has otherwise reached the approval threshold;
10 wishes to make a request for exclusion from the district, to be
11 approved or denied by the legislative body before the final
12 passage of the ordinance establishing the district.
13 Sec. 13. (a) After conducting a hearing on the proposed district,
14 the legislative body may adopt an ordinance establishing the
15 district if it determines that:
16 (1) the petition meets the requirements of this section and
17 sections 9 through 11 of this chapter;
18 (2) the activities and improvements to be undertaken in the
19 district will provide special benefits to businesses in the
20 district and will be of public utility and benefit;
21 (3) the benefits provided by the activities and improvements
22 will be new benefits that do not replace benefits existing
23 before the establishment of the district; and
24 (4) the formula or method to be used for the assessment of
25 special benefits is appropriate.
26 (b) The legislative body may adopt the ordinance only if it
27 determines that the petition has been signed by:
28 (1) at least fifty percent (50%) of the owners of businesses
29 within the proposed district; and
30 (2) the owners of businesses within the proposed district that
31 constitute more than fifty percent (50%) of the revenue to be
32 collected from the special assessments.
33 (c) The ordinance shall:
34 (1) incorporate the information set forth in the district plan;
35 (2) specify the time and manner in which special assessments
36 levied under this chapter are to be collected and paid to the
37 unit's fiscal officer for deposit in the tourism improvement
38 fund established under section 14 of this chapter; and
39 (3) include any other content that the legislative body
40 determines is reasonable as it relates to the operation of the
41 district.
42 For purposes of subdivision (2), the collection of special
HB 1144—LS 6588/DI 129

6
1 assessments under this chapter may occur at the same time and in
2 the same manner as for an innkeeper's tax under IC 6-9, including
3 the application of any enforcement mechanisms and interest and
4 penalty attributable to innkeeper's taxes under IC 6-9-29.
5 (d) The adoption of an ordinance establishing a district does not
6 affect and may not be construed to authorize any decrease in the
7 level of publicly funded tourism promotion services that existed
8 before the district's establishment.
9 Sec. 14. (a) The unit's fiscal officer shall establish a special fund,
10 known as the tourism improvement fund, and shall deposit in the
11 tourism improvement fund all special assessments received under
12 this chapter and any other amounts received by the fiscal officer.
13 (b) The unit's fiscal officer may transfer money in the tourism
14 improvement fund to the district management association to be
15 used only for the purposes specified in the ordinance establishing
16 the district. Any bonds issued under this chapter are payable solely
17 from special assessments deposited in the tourism improvement
18 fund and other revenues of the district.
19 (c) Any money earned from investment of money in the tourism
20 improvement fund becomes a part of the tourism improvement
21 fund.
22 Sec. 15. (a) The unit shall contract with the district management
23 association designated in the district plan to administer and
24 implement the district's activities and improvements.
25 (b) The district management association may be either an
26 existing nonprofit corporation or a newly formed nonprofit
27 corporation. If the district management association is a new
28 nonprofit corporation created to manage the district, the certificate
29 of incorporation or bylaws of the district management association
30 shall provide for voting representation of owners within the
31 district. If the district management association is an existing
32 nonprofit corporation, the existing nonprofit corporation may
33 create a committee of district owners or owners' representatives.
34 (c) The district management association may make
35 recommendations to the unit's legislative body with respect to any
36 matter involving or relating to the district.
37 (d) The unit's legislative body, for any consideration that it
38 considers appropriate, may license or grant to the district
39 management association the right to undertake or permit
40 commercial activities or other private uses of the streets or other
41 parts of the district in which the unit has any real property
42 interest.
