1 Sec. 16. (a) A district may issue bonds to provide improvements.
2 The term of any bonds issued may not exceed ten (10) years. If a
3 district is renewed under section 17 of this chapter, the term of any
4 bonds issued may not exceed ten (10) years from the date of
5 renewal.
6 (b) Bonds issued under this chapter do not constitute an
7 indebtedness of the unit within the meaning of a constitutional or
8 statutory debt limitation.
9 Sec. 17. (a) The initial term for a district shall be at least three
10 (3) years and not more than ten (10) years.
11 (b) A district may be renewed for one (1) additional period of
12 not more than ten (10) years by following the procedures for the
13 initial establishment of a district as set forth in sections 9 through
14 13 of this chapter.
15 (c) If a district is renewed, any remaining revenues derived from
16 the levy of a special assessment, or any revenues derived from the
17 sale of assets acquired with the revenues, shall be transferred to the
18 renewed district. The following apply to the transfer of any
19 remaining revenues of a renewed district:
20 (1) If the renewed district includes a business not included in
21 the prior district, the remaining revenues shall be spent to
22 benefit only the business in the prior district.
23 (2) If the renewed district does not include a business included
24 in the prior district, the remaining revenues attributable to
25 the parcel shall be refunded to the owners of the business by
26 applying the method the district used under section 11 of this
27 chapter to calculate the special assessment before the renewal.
28 (d) The boundaries, special assessments, improvements, or
29 activities of a renewed district are not required to be the same as
30 the original or prior district.
31 Sec. 18. An ordinance adopted under section 13 of this chapter
32 may be amended if notice of the proposed amendment is published
33 and mailed in the manner provided by section 12 of this chapter.
34 However, if an amendment proposes to:
35 (1) levy a new or increased special assessment;
36 (2) change the district's boundaries; or
37 (3) issue a new bond;
38 the unit's legislative body shall require compliance with the
39 procedures set forth in sections 9 through 13 of this chapter before
40 amending the ordinance.
41 Sec. 19. (a) During the operation of the district, there shall be a
42 thirty (30) day period, beginning one (1) year after the date of the
HB 1144—LS 6588/DI 129

8
1 district's establishment and in each year thereafter, in which the
2 owners may request dissolution of the district in accordance with
3 this section.
4 (b) After a public hearing before the unit's legislative body, the
5 legislative body may dissolve a district by ordinance in either of the
6 following circumstances:
7 (1) If the legislative body finds there has been
8 misappropriation of funds, malfeasance, or a violation of law
9 in connection with the management of the district.
10 (2) At any time during the annual thirty (30) day period
11 described in subsection (a).
12 (c) Upon the written petitions of the owners or authorized
13 representatives of businesses in the district that pay fifty percent
14 (50%) or more of the special assessments levied, the unit's
15 legislative body shall pass a resolution of intention to dissolve the
16 district.
17 (d) The unit's legislative body shall first adopt a resolution of
18 intention to dissolve the district before the public hearing to
19 dissolve a district under this section. The resolution of intention
20 must include each of the following items:
21 (1) The reason for the dissolution.
22 (2) The time and place of the public hearing.
23 (3) A proposal to dispose of any assets acquired with the
24 revenues of the special assessments levied within the district.
25 The notice of the hearing on the resolution of intent to dissolve the
26 district shall be published in the manner provided by IC 5-3-1 and
27 must also be given by mail to the owner of each business subject to
28 a special assessment in the district. The legislative body shall
29 conduct the public hearing on the resolution of intention to dissolve
30 the district not later than thirty (30) days after the date the notice
31 is mailed to the assessed owners.
32 (e) The public hearing to dissolve the district shall be held not
33 more than sixty (60) days after the date of the adoption of the
34 resolution of intention.
35 (f) A dissolution of a district under this section has the effect of
36 repealing the ordinance adopted under section 13 of this chapter
37 that established the district.
38 Sec. 20. (a) The district management association shall submit an
39 annual report to the legislative body and the fiscal body before
40 January 1 of each year, beginning in the year after the first year of
41 the district's establishment.
42 (b) The report shall contain the following information:
HB 1144—LS 6588/DI 129

9
1 (1) The use of revenue collected from special assessments
2 levied under this chapter for that year.
3 (2) The activities and improvements to be provided for the
4 ensuing year and an estimate of the cost of providing the
5 activities and improvements for the ensuing year.
6 (3) The estimated amount of any surplus or deficit revenues
7 to be carried over from the prior year.
8 Sec. 21. (a) Upon the dissolution or expiration without renewal
9 of a district, any remaining revenues, after all outstanding debts
10 are paid, derived from the:
11 (1) levy of special assessments; or
12 (2) sale of assets acquired with the revenues of the district or
13 from bond reserve funds or construction funds;
14 shall be refunded to the owners located within the district on or
15 before the date of the district's dissolution or expiration without
16 renewal.
17 (b) The amount of the refund provided under subsection (a) to
18 an owner shall be determined by applying the method the district
19 used under section 11 of this chapter to calculate the special
20 assessment in the year:
21 (1) in which the district was dissolved or allowed to expire
22 without renewal; or
23 (2) before the district was dissolved or allowed to expire
24 without renewal if a special assessment had not been levied.
25 However, in lieu of providing a refund, the unit's legislative body
26 may instead elect to spend any remaining revenues on activities
27 and improvements specified in the ordinance that established the
28 district before its dissolution or expiration without renewal.
29 (c) Any liabilities incurred by the district are not an obligation
30 of the unit and are payable solely from the collection of special
31 assessments deposited in the special fund under section 14 of this
32 chapter and other revenues of the district.
33 Sec. 22. Notwithstanding any other provision of this chapter,
34 special assessments levied to pay the principal and interest on any
35 bonds issued under this chapter may not be reduced or terminated
36 if doing so would interfere with the timely retirement of the debt.
